sections.body:
There is a gap between what a hand-carried pack delivers and what a large weldment, heavy shaft, or thick casting demands. **Mobile units** fill it: wheel- or skid-mounted power supplies, rolled between bays or towed to the site, typically delivering **2,000–6,000 A** of AC and half-wave DC (some add full-wave DC), with duty cycles and current control a step up from portable gear.

The reason for mobile equipment is exactly that combination: **bench-class amperage that still goes to the work** — parts too heavy to bench, structures being fabricated in place, heavy sections where prods alone cannot raise the required field.

A mobile unit has no headstock, no tailstock, no bath system. You build the technique from **flexible cables and accessories**:

- wrap the cable into a coil for longitudinal magnetization — the low-fill-factor rule of thumb NI ≈ 45,000/(L/D) applies to a cable wrap just as it does to a bench coil;
- clamp or bolt contacts to the part for direct circular shots;
- run the cable through a bore as a central conductor;
- fire from a remote switch at the part.

The similarity to stationary equipment is nearly literal: a mobile unit **is** the transformer, rectifier, current control, and ammeter of a stationary machine in a rolling case — everything except the fixtures and the bath. Most also provide step-down demagnetization.
